Introduction¶

This report is on the topic of world education, and what factors positively or negatively impact a countries outcome in the realm of education. Our project aims to explore the inputs and outputs of education to achieve a better understanding as to what factors contribute to a postitive educational experience, as well as what a successful education system looks like. By understanding these factors, we can also look at different societal outcomes to learn the importance of a strong education and how they relate to positive societal outcomes.

We chose this dataset and the corresponding guiding questions to not only better understand what a positive education can do for countries, but also to gain appreciation for the high-quality and easily accessible education we have access to hear in Canada. We are fortunate enough to be exposed to a well-structured education system from a very young age, with seemingly infinite educational opportunities even after high school. It is very easy to take our education system for granted, and through our exploration of our dataset, we hope to gain a better appreciation and understand as to how fortunate we really are to have the opportunities we do in Canada.

Dataset and Guiding Questions¶

Dataset¶

The dataset that we are going to be working with is an education statistics dataset published by the World Bank Group. This dataset was first published in 2010 and updated most recently in 2024. The dataset contains 3665 metrics across 242 regions. This dataset was aggregated by the World Bank Group from many different data sources, combining them into one large dataset. This is how it has such a wide variety of metrics measured across so many different regions.

The dataset contains data for each year from 1970 to 2017, and then every 5 years from 2020 to 2100, as it includes projections for some of the metrics as well. These years are listed as columns, and each rows represents a combination of which metric and what region. For example, row 360,500 is "Gross enrolment ratio, primary to tertiary, male (%), in Ghana", and across this row for each year column is either the value of the metric for that year, or NaN if no data was collected was collected. The original dataset has a total of 69 columns and 886,931 rows.

The license to use this dataset is Creative Commons Attribution 4.0, which means that it is free to use and adapt as long as the correct citation is present.

Interesting Aspects¶

The things that interested us in this dataset are actually the same things which hinder us while using this dataset. We were very interested in this dataset because of its wide range of metrics as well as years that it contains. Thousands of metrics and over 5 million total data points is an amazing dataset to look into, leveraging the power of python. However, this does cause us problems as well.

One thing is the amount of columns that is contained in this dataset. There are 66 columns for years, ranging from 1970-2100. This of course is not ideal for a dataset that we want to do analysis on because we would have to search through many columns depending on the year we want to look at. To deal with this problem we are going to have to convert our "Wide" dataset, to a "Long" dataset with only one column for "Year". The resulting dataset will have rows containing a single value (or NaN) indexed by a combination of metric, year, and region.

Another interesting aspect of this dataset is how the metrics are set up. Instead of having a column for each metric, where you could just compare two columns to each other when wanting to look for a correlation. There is actually just one column that lists each metric. This makes the analysis part of our project much more difficult because instead of just being able to look at two different columns, we have to create two new sub data frames that only contain the certain metric that we are looking at. On top of that, we then need to ensure that we can match up each country and year with its corresponding values for both of the metrics. There may be some years and countries who only have data for one of the metrics and not the other. If this were in a data frame where the metrics are the columns we would be able to just drop any rows that contain and Na's and analyse the two columns data. Because of the fact that we have over 3,000 metrics, it is not suitable to change the metrics to be columns and thus this is a problem that is going to have to be dealt with.

## functions to parse the indicators and the country names ##

def listtopics():
    """ list all series topics
    """
    return list(edseries.Topic.unique())

def get_indicators_by_topic(topic):
    """ display indicators under the give `topic` name.
    """
    return list(edseries[edseries.Topic == topic]["Indicator Name"].values)

def get_indicators_containing(contains):
    """ display indicator names containing the word `contains`
    """
    mask = [(contains in str) for str in edseries["Indicator Name"].values]
    return edseries[mask]["Indicator Name"].values

def get_series_code(indicator_name):
    """ return the series code based on given indicator name
    """
    return edseries[ edseries["Indicator Name"] == indicator_name ].index.values[0]

def get_country_code_by_name(countryname):
    """ pass in "Canada" to get "CAN", etc
    """
    return edcountry[edcountry["Short Name"] == countryname].index[0]

def get_country_name_by_code(countrycode):
    """ pass in "CAN" to get "Canada"
    """
    return edcountry.loc[countrycode]["Short Name"]

## functions to get a list of topics, sorted by how many rows of data
def get_indicators_by_topic_sorted(topic, cutoff=1, howmany=-1):
    """ print out all indicators under a given topic (with more than cutoff rows),
    and how many rows of data they have. prints out `howmany` results (or all, if howmany<=0) """
    printcount = 0 # increment counter

    # indicator code by occurances (most data to least data)
    howmuchdata = edstats.groupby(["Indicator Code"])["Rating"].count().sort_values(ascending=False)

    # table header
    print("Count  | Metric \n-------|---------")

    # show all metrics by name, sorted by size of data:
    for code in howmuchdata.index.values: # loop through metrics
        datacount = howmuchdata.loc[code] # current count
        if datacount >= cutoff: # if count is greater than cutoff
            try: # avoid errors
                if edseries.loc[code]["Topic"] == topic: # check topic matches
                    if howmany <= 0:
                        # if everythings good, print it out
                        print(f"{datacount:6d} | {edseries.loc[code, 'Indicator Name']}")
                    elif printcount < howmany:
                        print(f"{datacount:6d} | {edseries.loc[code, 'Indicator Name']}")
                        printcount += 1
            except:
                pass

def get_indicators_containing_sorted(keyword, cutoff=1, howmany=-1):

## functions to get a subset of the data ##

def get_data_by_code(code, yearstart=1970, yearend=2100):
    """ get dataframe by indicator code
    """
    yearmask = (edstats.Year >= yearstart) & (edstats.Year <= yearend)
    return edstats[yearmask].loc[code]

def get_data_by_name(name, yearstart=1970, yearend=2100):
    """ get dataframe by indicator name
    """
    return get_data_by_code(get_series_code(name), yearstart=yearstart, yearend=yearend)

Guiding Question 1:¶

How greatly does the pupil to teach ratio affect both the quality of education provided, and the success rate of students?

To answer this question we are going to be looking at the main variable of pupil to teacher ratio. This is the main variable of interest because we want to see how changes in this may have affects on other aspects of the quality of schooling such as the success rate of students and how many of them continue on to higher education.

We have to keep in mind that it is difficult to prove more than correlation, especially when there are lots of other factors that could be affecting these variables, such as GDP. Because of this we will always take a look at the GDP correlation to these metrics as well to ensure that we are providing a well-rounded view of our data and factors that may affect it.

This is great news for the education system, but can we see if these metrics are correlated to each other?

To do this we are going to have to combine our datasets and only have the resulting rows where data is present for both of the metrics, for a certain year and region. We can merge the first two data frames by common country and year, and then merge this one with GDP to add the third one.

The first analysis we are going to look at is the correlation between pupil-teacher ratio and the percent of students repeating a grade.

Pupil to Teacher Ratio¶

In [17]:
#Restating all the sub datasets to look at 2005 to 2015
puptoteach = get_data_by_name("Pupil-teacher ratio in primary education (headcount basis)", 2005, 2015)
repeaters = get_data_by_name("Percentage of repeaters in primary education, all grades, both sexes (%)", 2005, 2015)
grossenrolment = get_data_by_name("Gross enrolment ratio, upper secondary, both sexes (%)", yearstart=2005, yearend=2015)
gdp = get_data_by_name("GDP per capita (current US$)", 2005, 2015)

puptorepeat = pd.merge(puptoteach, repeaters, on=["Country Code","Year"], how='inner',suffixes=('_ptot','_repeat'))
puptorepeatgdp = pd.merge(puptorepeat, gdp, on=["Country Code","Year"], how='inner')

grosstopupil = pd.merge(puptoteach, grossenrolment, on=["Country Code","Year"], how='inner', suffixes=('_ptot','_gross'))
grosstopupilgdp = pd.merge(grosstopupil, gdp, on=["Country Code","Year"], how='inner')

One thing to note is that the suffixes only get applied to column names when there are duplicate columns names. During our second merge there are not going to be any duplicate column names and thus we have not supplied any suffixes.

We now have the sufficient data needed to make a scatter plot of the pupil-teacher ratio versus the percentage of repeaters in a grade. We are going to start by looking at some of the years by themselves to get a picture of whether or not the relationship may be changing.

Unsurprisingly, we do see that the countries with the higher GDP's tend to have smaller pupil to teacher ratios as well as less students repeating a grade. However, this does not mean that it pupil to teacher is less significant. It is very possible that the reason that these countries have a smaller percentage of students repeating a grade is entirely based on the pupil to teacher ratio, and the pupil to teacher ratio is often reflected by the GDP per capita.

But this is not always the case and we can look at some specific cases to illustrate this.

These examples show us that it is possible, independent of GDP, that a lower pupil to teacher ratio can help the success rates of students.

We see that the correlation coefficient between our two main metrics of interest, pupil-teacher ratio and the percent of students repeating a grade is actually the highest out of all the correlation coefficients that we calculated at a strong 0.676. This further helps illustrate that although GDP per capita does have an effect, it does not have the strongest correlation with our metrics of interest.

Additionally, to further test our hypothesis of whether or not pupil-teacher ratio affects the success of students we are also going to look at the gross enrollment rate in upper secondary.

Gross Enrollment Rate in Upper Secondary¶

Gross enrolment rate, as defined by the World Bank Group, can actually be above 100%. This is because they take the number of children who are in the defined age for a certain grade, and then use that as the denominator and the numerator as the amount of children in that grade. However, you can have cases were a grade may have more students in it, that do not actually fit into the age range, and thus the gross enrollment rate could be over 100%.

When the metric says 'upper secondary' which is defined as schooling for ages of around 16-19. For Canada for example we would call this high school.

Similar to the last metric, we are going to start by looking at how it has changed over the years.

Overall, our analysis in this guiding question shows that as we give more people access to the internet, the odds of having to repeat a grade drops. Although we see a moderate negative correlation between the two variables, it is important to note that this dataset goes back before the internet was widely accessible to the general public. Since the internet has become a staple in most countries, the percent of grade repeaters drops significantly.

  • Enrolment in tertiary education, all programmes, both sexes (number)

Since Enrolment by total number may be influenced by the size of a country, we can skip this first one.

Enrolment per 100,000 inhabitants is out of the total population, while gross enrolment ratio (GER) is the ratio of the number students enrolled in tertiary education expressed as a percentage of population who have graduated secondary education within the last 5 years. This number can be higher than 100% if a large amount of enrollment comes from students who enroll earlier or later than this 5 year period. Since we also have GER for non-tertirary schooling which may be interesting, it may be a better comparison to use GER for both cases.

The reading scale performance can be used as a reflection of the quality of education received. There are also similar scores for mathematics and science if needed.

Finally, we have GDP adjusted for inflation and converted to USD, as well as spending on education (overall) and tertiary education, both as a percentage of the GDP.

The gross enrollment rates (GER) seem to overall decrease, whereby the most common result is a country having a low GER. Reading scores increase from around 350 to a peak at 500 points. Most countries seem to have a GDP below 5 trillion, with a small handful of countries in the 30 trillion range. The distribution of spending on education is mostly bell shaped around 4%, skewing right towards a few countries that spend around 10%. Spending on tertiary is similarly distributed, but with a peak around 0.75%

We can also compare how these values change over time on average:

In [44]:

We can see over time, the enrollment rate in tertiary education seems to increase over time, from less than 10% in the 70's to almost 45% in the last few years. The drop-off at the end appears to be due to a single datapoint (perhaps not all countries have reported GER yet for the latest year, so the average is not fully representitive). Similarly, GER for non-tertiary post-secondary (vocational) seems to increase over time (with an errant datapoint at the end again). Reading score do not seem to have enough data to pick out any sort of trend (since there are only 6 years with data, perhaps different countries are represented in some data points and not others). GDP increases over time as we would expect. Percentage spent on education seems to have increased slightly since the 70's, hovering around 4-5%. Spending on tertiary education seems to hover around 1%, with a recent dropoff that is probably something similar to the errant data we saw in the GER plots.

To plot relationships between variables, we can pick a few of the metrics to combine (Not too many, since there is likely less overlap the more we pick). Here we pick tertiary GER, reading performance, and total GDP.

In [45]:
def merge_dataframes(dflist, colnames, on=["Country Code", "Year"], how="inner"):
    """ merge an arbitrary length list of dataframes `dflist` by the `on` columns.
    rename the merged columns based on the list `colnames`, which should be the
    same length as `dflist`. returns a single dataframe
    """
    from functools import reduce
    mergeddf = reduce(lambda left,right: pd.merge(left,right,on=on, how=how), dflist)
    mergeddf.columns = on + colnames
    return mergeddf

From the above analysis, we can see that there seems to be a small correlation between the success of students in the classroom and how many go on towards higher education. Furthermore, there seems to be no effect on this from GDP. Overall, while some of the variation (about $r^2=0.56^2\approx 0.31$) in enrollment rates can be explained by success in the classroom, this is a very complicated system and there are likely many other factors that affect this. In addition, success in the classroom is difficult to accurately represent by a single value.

GPI stands for gender parity index, it is female group value divided by male group value. When it is 1, it means equal between the two groups. If it is greater than 1, that will indicate favouring female, if it is less than 1, that means favouring male.

Looking at the primary education enrolment ratio(GPI) graph, we can see males are being favoured with a approximate value of 0.8 from 1970 to a approximate value of 0.975 in 2010. Secondary education enrolment looks similiar to the primary education enrolment with a approximate value of 0.75 at 1970 to a approximate value of 0.95 at 2010. Post-secondary education enrolment data is different from others, there is no data between 1970 and 1997, and female is being favoured from 1998 with a approximate value of 1.2 and keeping in a range of 1.1 to 1.3. Tertiary education enrolment data is similar to primary and secondary, but with more favours on male since the index value was around 0.55 in 1970. It reached a value of 1 around 2000 and kept moving up very slowly to be female favoured.

Overall, primary, secondary and terriary education were favoring male in the old days, but we have reached equality with the gender parity index value to be around 1 on education in 2010 based on the data. For higher education like post-secondary and tertiary, female is a little bit more favoured comparing to male nowadays.

We think government expenditure on education as percentage of GDP is hightly possible to correlate with education progress and thus building euqality between male and female, so we will look at it next.

Discussion and Conclusion¶

In general, our process was to first find two metrics relating to the guiding question, and then filter down the data to a subset of only the regions and years which have data for the metrics. We could then investigate the distributions and patterns in these metrics, and see if there is any correlation between the two.

Guiding Question 1¶

For our first question, we wanted to analyze the affect that the pupil to teacher ratio has on the success of students. The metrics that we used for this analysis in addition to the pupil to teacher ratio was the percentage of students repeating a grade and the gross enrollment rate in upper secondary school. When looking at the pupil to teacher ratio and the percent of students repeating a grade we saw that there was a positive linear relationship with a correlation coefficient of ($r=0.676$). This would state that as the pupil to teacher ratio decreases, the percent of students repeating a grade would also decrease. Although this is a significant correlation coefficient it is difficult to state that these two metrics have a causation relationship because there are so many other things that could possibly be affecting them.

When looking at the relationship between the pupil to teacher ratio and the gross enrollment rate in upper secondary school we see that there is a negative relationship with a correlation coefficient of ($r=-0.811$). This is a strong negative relationship between the two metrics and it would seem that as you decrease the pupil to teacher ratio the amount of students who go on to further education increases. This would make logical sense because as the students get more one on one time with the teacher they are more likely to succeed and continue furthering their education. However, we can not say with certainty that the pupil to teacher ratio causes the gross enrollment rates to change.

Guiding Question 2¶

For our second guiding question, we wanted to see if there was a relationship between internet users in a country compared to the percentage of grade repeaters. For this question, we used the metrics of internet users per 100, which shows us the average number of people with internet access per 100 people in a given country, and percent of grade repeaters, which is the percent of students that have to repeat a grade in primary education.

Our initial analysis showed that these two variable showed a similar shape of a graph when compared side by side, suggesting early on that there may be some correlation. When comparing the two variables side by side over a time horizon, we started to notice a difference. Evidently, as the internet becomes more commonplace in many different societies, the number of mean internet users has increased over time. For the percent of grade repeaters, the opposite seems to be true. We could hypothesize many different reasons for this, however it is too big of a question to analyze for our project. Finally, we compared the two in different years, to show how the increase in internet access has impacted the number of grade repeaters. In 5 year instalments, starting in 2005, we can see that the number of internet users has risen, and the percent of grade repeaters has creeped closer and closer to the axis.

In our final graph, we showed the linear regression of our model. Our linear regression line had a negative slope of $-1.53$, meaning for every 1% increase in grade repeaters, the number of internet users per 100 drops by 1.53. Our correlation coefficient was calculated as $-0.436$, suggesting a moderate negative correlation between the two variables. We determined that this is a reasonable answer, as we can expect there to be some negative correlation between the two variables from a common sense standpoint, yet the question is too large to be explained by only these two variables.

Guiding Question 3¶

For this analysis, we wanted to look into the effect of education quality on enrollment in higher education. The specific metrics we look at were tertiary gross enrollment ratio (GER), which tells us the ratio between the number of students enrolled in post-secondary to the number of recent graduates of secondary education. We compared this to reading scores that occured a few years prior, as a measure of the quality of education received. We found only a mild positive linear correlation ($r=0.56$) between these two, indicating there is some effect on enrollment rates from the quality of education received, but the system is extremely complicated and there are likely other factors at play. This aligns roughly with what we may expect, whereby a student who does very well in school likely finds learning worthwhile and may be inspired to pursue further education. Additionally, there are lots of reasons why one may decide not to pursue education, and so it makes sense we do not see a perfect correlation, and there are other effects in play.

We also looked at correlation between each metric and the countries GDP, and found there was no worthwhile correlation, with correlation coefficients of $r=0.16$ for GER and $r=0.21$ for Reading Performance. This is surprising, because at first it seems like countries that have more money to put into education would see larger returns in quality of education and would be more likely to have a large proportion of students going on to higher education, but this does not appear to be the case.

Guiding Question 4¶

We are examining gender differences and trends through the gross enrolment ratio of the gender parity index across multiple education levels. Males were significantly favoured starting in 1970, but by 2010, enrolment rates between males and females had become almost equal based on the data. In advanced education levels, such as post-secondary and tertiary, females are even favoured more than males. We analyzed government expenditure on education as a percentage of GDP and literacy rates to find correlations with gender differences. Unfortunately, we cannot establish a correlation between government expenditure on education and gender differences based on data from 1998 to 2010, as a long period of data is missing. However, we found a strong correlation between literacy rates and gender differences: 0.80 for primary and secondary education, and 0.50 for post-secondary and tertiary education. This finding supports the idea that higher family education levels reduce gender inequality. Today, there are no significant gender differences in education, and females are slightly favoured over males in advanced education.

Overall¶

As we explored through our guiding questions, education is definitely a crucial part for everyone. Better education will increase the chance of getting a higher quality of life. We have found some correlations between education indicators such as the pupil-to-teacher ratio, percentage of grade repeaters, and life indicators such as internet access rate and GDP. On the other hand, the trend of gender equality in education and the progress of the literacy rate and their highly positive correlation show us how better education leads to progress and a more equal society. In conclusion, education is a huge and complex system that involves economic and social factors that correlate to the quality of our lives.
